<author><name><![CDATA[Memblers]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-01-07T16:16:41-07:00</updated>
<published>2009-01-07T16:16:41-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4705&amp;p=41478#p41478</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4705&amp;p=41478#p41478"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Timing in NES, other than waiting for VBLANK]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4705&amp;p=41478#p41478"><![CDATA[
The easy way to get flexible timing at 60hz is to use sub-frame counting with 16-bit adds.  Just make it so the lower byte is never reset (always carries over).<br /><br />To your timer (16-bit variable), you'd add values like these every frame to get these rates:<br />$0100 = 60Hz.<br />$0001 = 1/256Hz<br />$0180 = 90Hz<br /><br />I guess you actually could just ditch the high byte and trigger a beat whenever the low byte wraps around (check carry flag).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Wed Jan 07, 2009 4:16 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
</entry>
